So, here's the story on the Skeptic Magazine article.

Two years ago, Scott McCrea published an article in (Vol 9, #4), which
demonstrated that the education available to Shakespeare in Stratford was
sufficient to explain the learning seen in the plays; the focus was
relatively narrow. I remember reading this article and finding it quite
reasonable. Subsequent issues published a few letters in response. As I
recall these came from nominal skeptics - people who explicitly rejected the
plausibility of ghosts, alien autopsies, etc. based on the pure lack of
evidence - but who were inclined to accept the plausibility of the
anti-Stratford case. I recall drafting a letter pointing out the inherent
implausibility of the anti-Stratford case, but I don't think I ever sent it
... certainly it was not published if I did. I haven't been reading the
magazine regularly for a year or so, so I don't know if the argument has
continued.

Now (Vol 11, #3; the issue is on the newsstands now), Price presents
arguments, very familiar to us, such as the lack of a &quot;contemporary literary
trail&quot;. As with the letter writers, she argues that doubting Shakespeare's
authorship is a reasonable skeptical position to take.

In my opinion she can only make this case by ignoring the context of the
evidence, as was true with her book. But making cases like this is not my
forte. I'd like to suggest to Mssrs Kathman and Reedy that they read the
article and consider sending a response to Price's article. We skeptics
like to think we have open minds, and I think the superficial plausibility
of Price's arguments, unrefuted, will appeal to those who don't have the
full picture.

