Editor: Your readers were really scammed by Diana Price's article in
the Vol. 11 No. 3 issue of SKEPTIC. This article has been cleverly
written with weasel words, half-truths, etc., to support her
pre-conceived idea that there is no evidence from Shakespeare's lifetime
that shows he was a writer. Here is just one example: She claims on p.15
that the famous 1592 reference to the &quot;Upstart Crow who pretends to be
able to bombast out a blank verse&quot; shows that Shakespeare is an actor.
But &quot;to bombast out&quot; in Elizabethan English meant &quot;to fill out&quot; or &quot;to
pad out.&quot; (Literally, it comes from &quot;cotton stuffing.&quot;) It's what poets
did in those days when they wrote lines to fit the required meter. It
had nothing to do with speaking, shouting, etc., like it does today. Any
Shakespearean or Elizabethan reference work will confirm this; it is not
controversial. Yet Price must use the modern meaning to justify her
theory, and must hope that no one will notice. There's other evidence
that Shakespeare was referred to as a writer in his lifetime, but I
charge for that. Incidentally, the desire to &quot;prove&quot; that Shakespeare
was not a writer is an attempt to ward off deeply buried feelings of
inadequacy; by belittling a great person one can elevate the self. Also,
by substituting a nobleman for the strictly middle-class Shakespeare,
today's Joe Blow can be admittedly less than Shakespeare, but still
great. Sincerely, -- Joe Mulligan

